  <span id="freeText3168270374887020265" style="display:none">I read 'Chesapeake' some thirty years ago - yet the vivid memories and impact of it are still with me today so that I intend to reread it again if time ever permits ! I mention the time factor because it sits in that genre of massive 'blockbusters'(alongside 'War And Peace') - the size of a brick and unputdownable !<br /><br />In this masterpiece, James A. Michener encapsulates almost the entire history of America within the microcosm of the Chesapeake Bay area, with its ancient abundance of fish, herons and geese. From the time when the native Indians first saw the 'Great Canoe'of the first settlers (who, as pilgrims, farmers, hunters, slaves, merchants and watermen came over the next four centuries) - to the late 1970's, this mammoth novel reflects all the diversity, excitement, violence and charisma of burgeoning American society - seen, especially, through the turbulent stories of four imaginary families with their lives, deaths, triumphs, disasters, happiness and hell. <br /><br />For anybody wishing to discover the real origins of the USA - this book is compulsory reading - but not always for the squeamish !</span>
